{"title_page": "James Phipps", "text_new": "{{about||the Australian footballer|Jim Phipps|the Captain-General of the Royal African Company|James Phipps of Cape Coast Castle}}\n\n[[File:Jenner phipps 01.jpg|thumbnail|Dr Jenner performing his first vaccination on James Phipps, a boy of age 8. May 14th, 1796. Painting by Ernest Board (early 20th century).]]\n'''James Phipps''' (1788 \u2013 25 April 1853) was the first person given the [[cowpox]] vaccine by [[Edward Jenner]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Reid, Robert |title=Microbes and men |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |page=7|location=London |year=1974 |isbn=0-563-12469-5 }}</ref> Jenner knew of a local belief that dairy workers who had contracted a relatively mild infection called [[cowpox]] were immune to [[smallpox]]. \n<ref>{{cite book |last=Bartolache |first=Jos\u00e9 Ignacio |year=1779 |title=Instrucci\u00f3n que puede servir para que se cure a los enfermos de las viruelas epidemicas que ahora se padecen en M\u00e9xico |edition=1st |language=Spanish |publisher = Impresa \u00e0 instancia y expensas de dicha N. Ciudad }}</ref>\n\n== Early life and vaccination against smallpox ==\nPhipps was born in [[Berkeley, Gloucestershire|Berkeley]] parish in Gloucestershire to a poor, landless labourer working as Jenner's gardener. He was baptised in St Mary's parish church, Berkeley, when he was 4.<ref>http://histclo.com/child/chron/mod/18/c18-phi.html</ref>\n\n[[file:Melingue Jenner.jpg|thumbnail|[[Lithograph]] depicting the inoculation of James Phipps, by Gaston M\u00e9lingue (circa 1894)]]\n\nOn 14&nbsp;May 1796 he was selected by Jenner, who took \"a healthy boy, about eight years old for the purpose of inoculation for the Cow Pox\".<ref>Reid, p. 18</ref> Jenner took some fluid from the cowpox vesicles on the hand of a milkmaid named Sarah Nelmes (in an unpublished manuscript Jenner refers to her as ''Lucy Nelmes''<ref>D. Baxby: [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1139508/?tool=pubmed ''The genesis of Edward Jenner's Inquiry of 1798: a comparison of the two unpublished manuscripts and the published version.''] In: ''Med Hist'' 29, 1985, S.&nbsp;193\u2013199. {{PMID|3884936}}</ref>), and inoculated Phipps by two small cuts in the skin of the boy's arm.\n\nJenner wrote: ''On the seventh day he complained of uneasiness in the [[axilla]] and on the ninth he became a little chilly, lost his appetite, and had a slight headache. During the whole of this day he was perceptibly indisposed, and spent the night with some degree of restlessness, but on the day following he was perfectly well.''<ref>{{cite journal | year = 2004 | title = Tan: ''Edward Jenner (1749\u20131823)  conqueror of smallpox.'' | url = | journal = Singapore Med J | volume = 45 | issue = 11| pages = 507\u2013508 | pmid = 15510320  | last1 = Tan | first1 = SY}}</ref> About six weeks later Jenner inoculated the boy with smallpox which had no effect, and concluded that he now had complete protection against smallpox.<ref name=\"PMID17302886\">A. J. Morgan and S. Parker: [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1810486/?tool=pubmed ''Translational Mini-Review Series on Vaccines: The Edward Jenner Museum and the history of vaccination.''] ''Clin Exp Immunol'' 147, 389\u2013394. {{PMID|17302886}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Willis | first1 = N. J. | year = 1997 | title = Edward Jenner and the eradication of smallpox. | url = | journal = Scott Med J | volume = 42 | issue = 4| pages = 118\u2013121 | pmid = 9507590 }}</ref> Phipps was subsequently inoculated with smallpox more than twenty times without succumbing to the disease.<ref>Reid, p. 19</ref>\n\nPhipps is often cited incorrectly as the first person to be vaccinated against smallpox by inoculation with cowpox: other people had undergone the procedure before him. In 1791, [[Peter Plett]] from [[Kiel]] in the [[Duchy of Holstein]] (now [[Germany]]) inoculated three children,<ref>P. C. Plett: ''Peter Plett und die \u00fcbrigen Entdecker der Kuhpockenimpfung vor Edward Jenner.'' ''Sudhoffs Archiv'', Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Wissenschaftsgeschichte, vol 90, issue 2, Franz Steiner Verlag, Stuttgart, 2006, pp.&nbsp;219\u2013232. {{ISSN|0039-4564}}</ref> and [[Benjamin Jesty]] of [[Yetminster]] in [[Dorset]] performed the procedure on three family members in 1774.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Hammarsten | first1 = J. F. | display-authors = etal | year = 1979 | title = Who discovered smallpox vaccination? Edward Jenner or Benjamin Jesty? | journal = Trans Am Clin Climatol Assoc | volume = 90 | issue = | pages = 44\u201355 | pmid = 390826 | pmc = 2279376 }}</ref> However, Jenner included his description of the vaccination of Phipps and an illustration of the hand of Sarah Nelmes from which the material was taken in his ''Inquiry'' published in 1798. Together with a series of vaccinations which showed that the vaccine could be maintained by arm to arm transfer, and  information about selection of suitable material, Jenner's ''Inquiry'' was the first published account of vaccination.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Baxby|first=Derrick|title=Edward Jenner's Inquiry; a bicentenary analysis|journal=Vaccine|year=1999|volume=17|issue=4|pages=301\u2013307|pmid=9987167|doi=10.1016/s0264-410x(98)00207-2}}</ref>\n\n== Later life ==\n[[File:James Phipps' Cottage - plaque.JPG|thumb|left]]\nLater in Phipps' life, Jenner gave him, his wife, and his two children a free lease on a cottage in Berkeley, which went on to house the ''Edward Jenner Museum'' between 1968 and 1982.<ref name=\"PMID17302886\" /> Phipps attended Jenner's funeral on 3&nbsp;February 1823.<ref>http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/broughttolife/people/jamesphipps.aspx</ref>\n\nIn 1853 Phipps was buried in St Mary's church in Berkeley, where he had been baptised. Jenner was also buried in this church.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/ockhamsrazor/defending-edward-jenner/3566216 ''Defending Edward Jenner''] - talk on ABC [[Radio National]] 1997\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Phipps, James}}\n[[Category:1788 births]]\n[[Category:1853 deaths]]\n[[Category:English children]]\n[[Category:18th-century English people]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Australian footballer|Jim Phipps}}\n{{for|the Captain-General of the Royal African Company|James Phipps of Cape Coast Castle}}\n[[File:Jenner phipps 01.jpg|thumbnail|Dr Jenner performing his first vaccination on James Phipps, a boy of age 8. May 14th, 1796. Painting by Ernest Board (early 20th century).]]\n'''James Phipps''' (1788 \u2013 25 April 1853) was the first person given the [[cowpox]] vaccine by [[Edward Jenner]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Reid, Robert |title=Microbes and men |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |page=7|location=London |year=1974 |isbn=0-563-12469-5 }}</ref> Jenner knew of a local belief that dairy workers who had contracted a relatively mild infection called [[cowpox]] were immune to [[smallpox]]. \n<ref>{{cite book |last=Bartolache |first=Jos\u00e9 Ignacio |year=1779 |title=Instrucci\u00f3n que puede servir para que se cure a los enfermos de las viruelas epidemicas que ahora se padecen en M\u00e9xico |edition=1st |language=Spanish |publisher = Impresa \u00e0 instancia y expensas de dicha N. Ciudad }}</ref>\n\n== Early life and vaccination against smallpox ==\nPhipps was born in [[Berkeley, Gloucestershire|Berkeley]] parish in Gloucestershire to a poor, landless labourer working as Jenner's gardener. He was baptised in St Mary's parish church, Berkeley, when he was 4.<ref>http://histclo.com/child/chron/mod/18/c18-phi.html</ref> \n\n[[file:Melingue Jenner.jpg|thumbnail|[[Lithograph]] depicting the inoculation of James Phipps, by Gaston M\u00e9lingue (circa 1894)]]\n\nOn 14&nbsp;May 1796 he was selected by Jenner, who took \"a healthy boy, about eight years old for the purpose of inoculation for the Cow Pox\".<ref>Reid, p. 18</ref> Jenner took some fluid from the cowpox vesicles on the hand of a milkmaid named Sarah Nelmes (in an unpublished manuscript Jenner refers to her as ''Lucy Nelmes''<ref>D. Baxby: [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1139508/?tool=pubmed ''The genesis of Edward Jenner's Inquiry of 1798: a comparison of the two unpublished manuscripts and the published version.''] In: ''Med Hist'' 29, 1985, S.&nbsp;193\u2013199. {{PMID|3884936}}</ref>), and inoculated Phipps by two small cuts in the skin of the boy's arm. \n\nJenner wrote: ''On the seventh day he complained of uneasiness in the [[axilla]] and on the ninth he became a little chilly, lost his appetite, and had a slight headache. During the whole of this day he was perceptibly indisposed, and spent the night with some degree of restlessness, but on the day following he was perfectly well.''<ref>S. Y.: Tan: ''Edward Jenner (1749\u20131823): conqueror of smallpox.'' In: ''Singapore Med J'' 45, 2004, pp.&nbsp;507\u2013508. {{PMID|15510320}}</ref> About six weeks later Jenner inoculated the boy with smallpox which had no effect, and concluded that he now had complete protection against smallpox.<ref name=\"PMID17302886\">A. J. Morgan and S. Parker: [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1810486/?tool=pubmed ''Translational Mini-Review Series on Vaccines: The Edward Jenner Museum and the history of vaccination.''] In: ''Clin Exp Immunol'' 147, 2007, S.&nbsp;389\u2013394. {{PMID|17302886}}</ref><ref>N. J. Willis: ''Edward Jenner and the eradication of smallpox.'' In: ''Scott Med J'' 42, 1997, pp.&nbsp;118\u2013121. {{PMID|9507590}}</ref> Phipps was subsequently inoculated with smallpox more than twenty times without succumbing to the disease.<ref>Reid, p. 19</ref>\n\nPhipps is often cited incorrectly as the first person to be vaccinated against smallpox by inoculation with cowpox: other people had undergone the procedure before him. In 1791, [[Peter Plett]] from [[Kiel]] in the [[Duchy of Holstein]] (now [[Germany]]) inoculated three children,<ref>P. C. Plett: ''Peter Plett und die \u00fcbrigen Entdecker der Kuhpockenimpfung vor Edward Jenner.'' In: ''Sudhoffs Archiv'', Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Wissenschaftsgeschichte, vol 90, issue 2, Franz Steiner Verlag, Stuttgart, 2006, pp.&nbsp;219\u2013232. {{ISSN|0039-4564}}</ref> and [[Benjamin Jesty]] of [[Yetminster]] in [[Dorset]] performed the procedure on three family members in 1774.<ref>J. F. Hammarsten et al.: [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2279376/?tool=pubmed ''Who discovered smallpox vaccination? Edward Jenner or Benjamin Jesty?''] In: ''Trans Am Clin Climatol Assoc'' 90, 1979, pp.&nbsp;44\u201355. {{PMID|390826}}</ref> However, Jenner included his description of the vaccination of Phipps and an illustration of the hand of Sarah Nelmes from which the material was taken in his ''Inquiry'' published in 1798. Together with a series of vaccinations which showed that the vaccine could be maintained by arm to arm transfer, and  information about selection of suitable material, Jenner's ''Inquiry'' was the first published account of vaccination.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Baxby|first=Derrick|title=Edward Jenner's Inquiry; a bicentenary analysis|journal=Vaccine|year=1999|volume=17|issue=4|pages=301\u2013307|pmid=9987167|doi=10.1016/s0264-410x(98)00207-2}}</ref>\n\n== Later life ==\n[[File:James Phipps' Cottage - plaque.JPG|thumb|left]]\nLater in Phipps' life, Jenner gave him, his wife, and his two children a free lease on a cottage in Berkeley, which went on to house the ''Edward Jenner Museum'' between 1968 and 1982.<ref name=\"PMID17302886\" /> Phipps attended Jenner's funeral on 3&nbsp;February 1823.<ref>http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/broughttolife/people/jamesphipps.aspx</ref>\n\nIn 1853 Phipps was buried in St Mary's church in Berkeley, where he had been baptised. Jenner was also buried in this church.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/ockhamsrazor/defending-edward-jenner/3566216 ''Defending Edward Jenner''] - talk on ABC [[R